Thiopurine metabolites have a half-life of several days so there is no need to sample at any special time. Steady state levels are reached at 2-4 weeks after a dose change. Suggested time of sampling for therapeutic monitoring is 4weeks after dose change.
Answers to the following questions are required by the analysing laboratory:
F6 - Liver Disease (no evidence of benefit in non-bleeding patients)
F5 - Massive Transfusion / Bleeding (ratio as per Massive Transfusion Protocol)
C4 - Fibrinogen <1.5g/l secondary to massive transfusion
P2 - Bone Marrow Failure - Plt count <20 - with additional risk factors e.g. sepsis
P10 - Immune Thrombocytopenia - Neonatal Alloimmune Thrombocytopenia, to maintain plts >30
P3 - Invasive procedures to raise Plt count >50 ( >80 for epidural anaesthesia >100 for eye surgery)
P4 - Critical Care/Surgery - Massive Blood Transfusion aim for >75 (or >100 if eye/brain trauma)
P5 - Critical Care/Surgery - Aquired Platelet Dysfunction e.g. ?drug induced bleeding, not surgically correctable
P6 - Critical Care/Surgery - Acute DIC with Bleeding and Thrombocytopenia
P7 - Critical Care/Surgery - Patients with Inherited Platelet Dysfunction Disorders
P8 - Immune Thrombocytopenia - Primary Immune Thrombocytopenia - for theatre cover or major haemorrhage. Aim for >80.
R4 - to correct Hb below 90g/l in sepsis, traumatic brain injury or cerebral ischaemia
R6 - Chronic anaemia - to alleviate symptoms when Hb >80g/l
R7 - Exchange transfusion
C3 - Bleeding associated with thrombolytic therapy causing fibrinogen to drop to <1.0g/l
